[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] In mathematics, a **Barnes integral** or **Mellin–Barnes integral** is a contour integral involving a product of gamma functions.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] They were introduced by Ernest William Barnes (1908, 1910).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] They are closely related to generalized hypergeometric series.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] The integral is usually taken along a contour which is a deformation of the imaginary axis passing to the right of all poles of factors of the form Γ(*a* + *s*) and to the left of all poles of factors of the form Γ(*a* − *s*).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] This equality can be obtained by moving the contour to the right while picking up the residues at *s* = 0, 1, 2, ... . for $z\ll 1$ , and by analytic continuation elsewhere.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] Given proper convergence conditions, one can relate more general Barnes' integrals and generalized hypergeometric functions *p**F**q* in a similar way (Slater 1966).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] This is an analogue of Gauss's 2*F*1 summation formula, and also an extension of Euler's beta integral.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] The integral in it is sometimes called **Barnes's beta integral**.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] This is an analogue of Saalschütz's summation formula.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/barnes-integral] There are analogues of Barnes integrals for basic hypergeometric series, and many of the other results can also be extended to this case (Gasper & Rahman 2004, chapter 4).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] In mathematics, **basic hypergeometric series**, or ***q*-hypergeometric series**, are *q*-analogue generalizations of generalized hypergeometric series, and are in turn generalized by elliptic hypergeometric series.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] A series *x**n* is called hypergeometric if the ratio of successive terms *x**n*+1/*x**n* is a rational function of *n*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] If the ratio of successive terms is a rational function of *q**n*, then the series is called a basic hypergeometric series.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] It becomes the hypergeometric series ${\displaystyle F(\alpha ,\beta$ in the limit when base $q=1$ .
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] There are two forms of basic hypergeometric series, the **unilateral basic hypergeometric series** φ, and the more general **bilateral basic hypergeometric series** ψ.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] This series is called *balanced* if *a*1 ...
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] The unilateral series can be obtained as a special case of the bilateral one by setting one of the *b* variables equal to *q*, at least when none of the *a* variables is a power of *q*, as all the terms with *n* < 0 then vanish.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] Here ${\begin{bmatrix}N\\n\end{bmatrix}}_{q}$ is a *q*-binomial coefficient.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] The special case of *a* = 0 is closely related to the *q*-exponential.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] Similar identities for $\;_{6}\psi _{6}$ have been given by Bailey.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] where the poles of $(aq^{s},bq^{s};q)_{\infty }$ lie to the left of the contour and the remaining poles lie to the right.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] There is a similar contour integral for *r*+1φ*r*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/basic-hypergeometric-series] This contour integral gives an analytic continuation of the basic hypergeometric function in *z*.
