[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] In mathematics, a **confluent hypergeometric function** is a solution of a **confluent hypergeometric equation**, which is a degenerate form of a hypergeometric differential equation where two of the three regular singularities merge into an irregular singularity.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] The term *confluent* refers to the merging of singular points of families of differential equations; *confluere* is Latin for "to flow together".
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] The Kummer functions, Whittaker functions, and Coulomb wave functions are essentially the same, and differ from each other only by elementary functions and change of variables.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] with a regular singular point at *z* = 0 and an irregular singular point at *z* = ∞.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Another common notation for this solution is Φ(*a*, *b*, *z*).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Considered as a function of a, b, or z with the other two held constant, this defines an entire function of a or z, except when *b* = 0, −1, −2, ...
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] As a function of b it is analytic except for poles at the non-positive integers.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Some values of a and b yield solutions that can be expressed in terms of other known functions.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] When a is a non-positive integer, then Kummer's function (if it is defined) is a generalized Laguerre polynomial.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] and many of the properties of the confluent hypergeometric function are limiting cases of properties of the hypergeometric function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Since Kummer's equation is second order there must be another, independent, solution.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] The indicial equation of the method of Frobenius tells us that the lowest power of a power series solution to the Kummer equation is either 0 or 1 − *b*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] This means that *z*1−*b**M*(*a* + 1 − *b*, 2 − *b*, *z*) is a solution so long as b is not an integer greater than 1, just as *M*(*a*, *b*, *z*) is a solution so long as b is not an integer less than 1.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] We can also use the Tricomi confluent hypergeometric function *U*(*a*, *b*, *z*) introduced by Francesco Tricomi (1947), and sometimes denoted by Ψ(*a*; *b*; *z*).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Although this expression is undefined for integer b, it has the advantage that it can be extended to any integer b by continuity.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Unlike Kummer's function which is an entire function of z, *U*(*z*) usually has a singularity at zero.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] But see #Special cases for some examples where it is an entire function (polynomial).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Note that the solution *z*1−*b**U*(*a* + 1 − *b*, 2 − *b*, *z*) to Kummer's equation is the same as the solution *U*(*a*, *b*, *z*), see #Kummer's transformation.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] For most combinations of real or complex a and b, the functions *M*(*a*, *b*, *z*) and *U*(*a*, *b*, *z*) are independent, and if b is a non-positive integer, so *M*(*a*, *b*, *z*) doesn't exist, then we may be able to use *z*1−*b**M*(*a*+1−*b*, 2−*b*, *z*) as a second solution.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] But if a is a non-positive integer and b is not a non-positive integer, then *U*(*z*) is a multiple of *M*(*z*).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] In that case as well, *z*1−*b**M*(*a*+1−*b*, 2−*b*, *z*) can be used as a second solution if it exists and is different.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] When *b* = 1 this is the exponential integral *E*1(*−z*).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] A similar problem occurs when *a*−*b* is a negative integer and b is an integer less than 1.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Note that for *M* = 0 or when the summation involves just one term, it reduces to the conventional Confluent Hypergeometric Equation.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/confluent-hypergeometric-function] Thus Confluent Hypergeometric Functions can be used to solve "most" second-order ordinary differential equations whose variable coefficients are all linear functions of z, because they can be transformed to the Extended Confluent Hypergeometric Equation.
