[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] When all the terms of the series are defined and it has a non-zero radius of convergence, then the series defines an analytic function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] Such a function, and its analytic continuations, is called the **hypergeometric function**.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] However, the use of the term *hypergeometric series* is usually restricted to the case where the series defines an actual analytic function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] The ordinary hypergeometric series should not be confused with the basic hypergeometric series, which, despite its name, is a rather more complicated and recondite series.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] The "basic" series is the q-analog of the ordinary hypergeometric series.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] There are several such generalizations of the ordinary hypergeometric series, including the ones coming from zonal spherical functions on Riemannian symmetric spaces.
