[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] Another generalization, the elliptic hypergeometric series, are those series where the ratio of terms is an elliptic function (a doubly periodic meromorphic function) of *n*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] During the twentieth century this was a fruitful area of combinatorial mathematics, with numerous connections to other fields.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] There are a number of new definitions of general hypergeometric functions, by Aomoto, Israel Gelfand and others; and applications for example to the combinatorics of arranging a number of hyperplanes in complex *N*-space (see arrangement of hyperplanes).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] Special hypergeometric functions occur as zonal spherical functions on Riemannian symmetric spaces and semi-simple Lie groups.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] In tensor product decompositions of concrete representations of this group Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are met, which can be written as 3*F*2 hypergeometric series.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] Bilateral hypergeometric series are a generalization of hypergeometric functions where one sums over all integers, not just the positive ones.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/generalized-hypergeometric-function] Fox–Wright functions are a generalization of generalized hypergeometric functions where the Pochhammer symbols in the series expression are generalised to gamma functions of linear expressions in the index *n*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] In mathematics, the Gaussian or ordinary **hypergeometric function** 2*F*1(*a*, *b*; *c*; *z*) is a special function represented by the **hypergeometric series**, that includes many other special functions as specific or limiting cases.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] It is a solution of a second-order linear ordinary differential equation (ODE).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Every second-order linear ODE with three regular singular points can be transformed into this equation.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] For systematic lists of some of the many thousands of published identities involving the hypergeometric function, see the reference works by Erdélyi et al.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] There is no known system for organizing all of the identities; indeed, there is no known algorithm that can generate all identities; a number of different algorithms are known that generate different series of identities.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The theory of the algorithmic discovery of identities remains an active research topic.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The term "hypergeometric series" was first used by John Wallis in his 1655 book *Arithmetica Infinitorum*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Hypergeometric series were studied by Leonhard Euler, but the first full systematic treatment was given by Carl Friedrich Gauss (1813).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Studies in the nineteenth century included those of Ernst Kummer (1836), and the fundamental characterisation by Bernhard Riemann (1857) of the hypergeometric function by means of the differential equation it satisfies.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Riemann showed that the second-order differential equation for 2*F*1(*z*), examined in the complex plane, could be characterised (on the Riemann sphere) by its three regular singularities.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The cases where the solutions are algebraic functions were found by Hermann Schwarz (Schwarz's list).
