[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The monodromy of a hypergeometric equation describes how fundamental solutions change when analytically continued around paths in the *z* plane that return to the same point.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] That is, when the path winds around a singularity of 2*F*1, the value of the solutions at the endpoint will differ from the starting point.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] In other words, the monodromy is a two dimensional linear representation of the fundamental group.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The monodromy group of the equation is the image of this map, i.e. the group generated by the monodromy matrices.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The monodromy representation of the fundamental group can be computed explicitly in terms of the exponents at the singular points.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] If 1 − *a*, *c* − *a* − *b*, *a* − *b* are non-integer rational numbers with denominators *k*, *l*, *m* then the monodromy group is finite if and only if $1/k+1/l+1/m>1$ , see Schwarz's list or Kovacic's algorithm.
