[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] When *z* is a real number greater than or equal to 1, analytic continuation must be used, because (1 − *zx*) is zero at some point in the support of the integral, so the value of the integral may be ill-defined.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] This was given by Euler in 1748 and implies Euler's and Pfaff's hypergeometric transformations.
