[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The Gauss hypergeometric function can be written as a John transform (Gelfand, Gindikin & Graev 2003, 2.1.2).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Gauss showed that 2*F*1(*a*, *b*; *c*; *z*) can be written as a linear combination of any two of its contiguous functions, with rational coefficients in terms of *a*, *b*, *c*, and z.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Transformation formulas relate two hypergeometric functions at different values of the argument *z*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] For extension of Euler's first and second transformations, see Rathie & Paris (2007) and Rakha & Rathie (2011).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] If two of the numbers 1 − *c*, *c* − 1, *a* − *b*, *b* − *a*, *a* + *b* − *c*, *c* − *a* − *b* are equal or one of them is 1/2 then there is a **quadratic transformation** of the hypergeometric function, connecting it to a different value of *z* related by a quadratic equation.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The first examples were given by Kummer (1836), and a complete list was given by Goursat (1881).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] If 1−*c*, *a*−*b*, *a*+*b*−*c* differ by signs or two of them are 1/3 or −1/3 then there is a **cubic transformation** of the hypergeometric function, connecting it to a different value of *z* related by a cubic equation.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] The first examples were given by Goursat (1881).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] There are also some transformations of degree 4 and 6.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/hypergeometric-function] Transformations of other degrees only exist if *a*, *b*, and *c* are certain rational numbers (Vidunas 2005).
