[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] In mathematics, the **G-function** was introduced by Cornelis Simon Meijer (1936) as a very general function intended to include most of the known special functions as particular cases.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] This was not the only attempt of its kind: the generalized hypergeometric function and the MacRobert E-function had the same aim, but Meijer's G-function was able to include those as particular cases as well.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] The first definition was made by Meijer using a series; nowadays the accepted and more general definition is via a line integral in the complex plane, introduced in its full generality by Arthur Erdélyi in 1953.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] With the modern definition, the majority of the established special functions can be represented in terms of the Meijer G-function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] A notable property is the closure of the set of all G-functions not only under differentiation but also under indefinite integration.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] The wide coverage of special functions also lends power to uses of Meijer's G-function other than the representation and manipulation of derivatives and antiderivatives.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] A still more general function, which introduces additional parameters into Meijer's G-function, is Fox's H-function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] One application of the Meijer G-function has been the particle spectrum of radiation from an inertial horizon in the moving mirror model of the dynamical Casimir effect (Good 2020).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] This integral is of the so-called Mellin–Barnes type, and may be viewed as an inverse Mellin transform.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Note that for historical reasons the *first* lower and *second* upper index refer to the *top* parameter row, while the *second* lower and *first* upper index refer to the *bottom* parameter row.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Implementations of the G-function in computer algebra systems typically employ separate vector arguments for the four (possibly empty) parameter groups *a*1 ...
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] *b**q*, and thus can omit the orders *p*, *q*, *n*, and *m* as redundant.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] The *L* in the integral represents the path to be followed while integrating.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] The conditions for convergence are readily established by applying Stirling's asymptotic approximation to the gamma functions in the integrand.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] When the integral converges for more than one of these paths, the results of integration can be shown to agree; if it converges for only one path, then this is the only one to be considered.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] In fact, numerical path integration in the complex plane constitutes a practicable and sensible approach to the calculation of Meijer G-functions.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] As a consequence of this definition, the Meijer G-function is an analytic function of *z* with possible exception of the origin *z* = 0 and of the unit circle |*z*| = 1.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] These particular solutions are analytic except for a possible singularity at *z* = 0 (as well as a possible singularity at *z* = ∞), and in the case of *p* = *q* also an inevitable singularity at *z* = (−1)*p*−*m*−*n*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] The star indicates that the term corresponding to *j* = *h* is omitted.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] For the integral to converge along the second path one must have either *p* < *q*, or *p* = *q* and |*z*| < 1, and for the poles to be distinct no pair among the *b**j*, *j* = 1, 2, ..., *m*, may differ by an integer or zero.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] this amounts to shortening the vector length from *q* to *q*−1.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] For this, either *p* > *q*, or *p* = *q* and |*z*| > 1 are required, and no pair among the *a**k*, *k* = 1, 2, ..., *n*, may differ by an integer or zero.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Apart from this restriction, the relationship is valid whenever the generalized hypergeometric series *p**F**q*(*z*) converges, i. e. for any finite *z* when *p* ≤ *q*, and for |*z*| < 1 when *p* = *q* + 1.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] In the latter case, the relation with the G-function automatically provides the analytic continuation of *p**F**q*(*z*) to |*z*| ≥ 1 with a branch cut from 1 to ∞ along the real axis.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Finally, the relation furnishes a natural extension of the definition of the hypergeometric function to orders *p* > *q* + 1.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] By means of the G-function we can thus solve the generalized hypergeometric differential equation for *p* > *q* + 1 as well.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Note that the first G-function vanishes for *n* = 0 if *p* > *q*, while the second G-function vanishes for *m* = 0 if *p* < *q*.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Again, the formula can be verified by expressing the two G-functions as sums of residues; no cases of confluent poles permitted by the definition of the G-function need be excluded here.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] As can be seen from the definition of the G-function, if equal parameters appear among the **a****p** and **b****q** determining the factors in the numerator and the denominator of the integrand, the fraction can be simplified, and the order of the function thereby be reduced.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Whether the order *m* or *n* will decrease depends on the particular position of the parameters in question.
