[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Here, *H* denotes the Heaviside step function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Even the derivatives of γ(*α*,*x*) and Γ(*α*,*x*) with respect to *α* can be expressed in terms of the Meijer G-function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/meijer-g-function] Here, γ and Γ are the lower and upper incomplete gamma functions, *J**ν* and *Y**ν* are the Bessel functions of the first and second kind, respectively, *I**ν* and *K**ν* are the corresponding modified Bessel functions, and Φ is the Lerch transcendent.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The value of each is taken to be 1 (an empty product) when $n=0$ .
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] These symbols are collectively called **factorial powers**.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The **Pochhammer symbol**, introduced by Leo August Pochhammer, is the notation $(x)_{n}$ , where n is a non-negative integer.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] It may represent *either* the rising or the falling factorial, with different articles and authors using different conventions.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] Pochhammer himself actually used $(x)_{n}$ with yet another meaning, namely to denote the binomial coefficient ${\tbinom {x}{n}}$ .
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] In this article, the symbol $(x)_{n}$ is used to represent the falling factorial, and the symbol $x^{(n)}$ is used for the rising factorial.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] These conventions are used in combinatorics, although Knuth's underline and overline notations $x^{\underline {n}}$ and $x^{\overline {n}}$ are increasingly popular.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] In the theory of special functions (in particular the hypergeometric function) and in the standard reference work *Abramowitz and Stegun*, the Pochhammer symbol $(x)_{n}$ is used to represent the rising factorial.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] When x is a positive integer, the falling factorial $(x)_{n}$ gives the number of n-permutations, sequences of n distinct elements) from an x -element set, or equivalently the number of injective functions from a set of size n to a set of size x .
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The rising factorial $x^{(n)}$ gives the number of partitions of an n -element set into x ordered sequences (possibly empty).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The coefficients that appear in the expansions are Stirling numbers of the first kind; see § Connection coefficients and identities below.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] When the variable x is a positive integer, the number $(x)_{n}$ is equal to the number of n-permutations from a set of x items, that is, the number of ways of choosing an ordered list of length n consisting of distinct elements drawn from a collection of size x .
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] For example, $(8)_{3}=8\times 7\times 6=336$ is the number of possible different podiums, assignments of gold, silver, and bronze medals in eight-person race.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] On the other hand, $x^{(n)}$ is "the number of ways to arrange n flags on x flagpoles", where all flags must be used and each flagpole can have any number of flags.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] Equivalently, this is the number of ways to partition a set of size n (the flags) into x disjoint parts (the flagpoles), with a linear order on the elements in each part (the order of the flags on each pole).
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The rising and falling factorials are well defined in any unital ring, and therefore x can be taken to be, for example, a complex number, including negative integers, or a polynomial with complex coefficients, or any complex-valued function.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] Note, however, that the hypergeometric function literature typically uses the notation $(a)_{n}$ for rising factorials.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] Falling and rising factorials are closely related to Stirling numbers.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] In this formula and in many other places, the falling factorial $(x)_{n}$ in the calculus of finite differences plays the role of $x^{n}$ in differential calculus.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] A corresponding relation holds for the rising factorial and the backward difference operator.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The study of analogies of this type is known as umbral calculus.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] A general theory covering such relations, including the falling and rising factorial functions, is given by the theory of polynomial sequences of binomial type and Sheffer sequences.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] where the coefficients are the same as those in the binomial theorem.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] Graham, Knuth, and Patashnik propose to pronounce these expressions as "x to the m rising" and "x to the m falling", respectively.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] An alternative notation for the rising factorial $x^{(n)}$ is the less common $(x)_{n}^{+}~.$ When $(x)_{n}^{+}$ is used to denote the rising factorial, the notation $(x)_{n}^{-}$ is typically used for the ordinary falling factorial, to avoid confusion.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] The Pochhammer symbol has a generalized version called the generalized Pochhammer symbol, used in multivariate analysis.
[src:hypergeometric-functions/pochhammer-symbol] There is also a q-analogue, the q-Pochhammer symbol.
